Code Sections / Segments

Pragma                   Description

#pragma alloc_text("seg", func)
                         Specify the code segment where named functions go. Function must be declared extern first.

#pragma bss_seg(["seg"])
                         Set the segment for uninitialized data (BSS). Supports push/pop with optional identifier.

#pragma code_seg(["seg"])
                         Set the segment for compiled function code. Supports push/pop.

#pragma const_seg(["seg"])
                         Set the segment for const data. Supports push/pop.
#pragma data_seg(["seg"])
                         Set the segment for initialized data. Supports push/pop.
#pragma section("name" [, attrs])
                         Create a named section in the .obj with optional attributes (read, write, execute, shared, nopage, nocache, discard, remove). Used with __declspec(allocate(...)).

Optimization

Pragma                   Description

#pragma auto_inline(on|off)
                         Enable/disable automatic inlining of functions.
#pragma inline_depth(n)  Set max inline call depth (0–255).

#pragma inline_recursion(on|off)
                         Enable/disable inlining of recursive functions.
#pragma intrinsic(func, ...)
                         Tell the compiler to generate intrinsic (inline) versions of listed functions (e.g. memcpy, strlen, sqrt).

#pragma function(func, ...)
                         Opposite of intrinsic — force actual function calls instead of intrinsics.
#pragma optimize("flags", on|off)
                         Enable/disable specific optimizations per-function. Flags: g (global), s (size), t (speed), y (frame pointer). Empty string "" + off disables all.

Struct / Memory Layout

PragmaDescription

#pragma pack([n])        Set struct member alignment to n bytes (1, 2, 4, 8, 16).

#pragma pack(push [, id] [, n])
                         Save current pack setting on a stack, optionally set new value.
#pragma pack(pop [, id|n])
                         Restore previously pushed pack setting.#pragma pack(show)Emit current pack value as a warning message.

Warnings & Diagnostics

Pragma                   Description

#pragma warning(disable : nnnn ...)
                         Disable specific warning numbers.
#pragma warning(enable : nnnn ...)
                         Enable specific warning numbers.
#pragma warning(error : nnnn ...)
                         Treat specific warnings as errors.
#pragma warning(default : nnnn ...)
                         Reset specific warnings to their default behavior.
#pragma warning(once : nnnn ...)
                         Show a specific warning at most once.
#pragma warning(suppress : nnnn ...)
                         Suppress warning for the next line only.
#pragma warning(push [, n])
                         Save current warning state (optionally set level to n).
#pragma warning(pop)     Restore last saved warning state.

#pragma message("text")  Print a message to the build output at compile time (doesn't stop compilation).

#pragma deprecated(name, ...)
                         Mark a function/type as deprecated; generates C4995 when used.
#pragma detect_mismatch("name", "value")
                         Embed a name/value record in the .obj; linker errors if mismatched across TUs. Useful for catching config mismatches.

Linker / Object File

Pragma                   Description

#pragma comment(lib, "name.lib")
                         Automatically link against a library (embeds lib name in .obj).
#pragma comment(linker, "/flag")
                         Pass a linker flag from source code (e.g. /INCLUDE:symbol).
#pragma comment(compiler)
                         Embed compiler name/version in the .obj.
#pragma comment(user, "text")
                         Embed a general text comment in the .obj.

Runtime Checks

Pragma                   Description

#pragma runtime_checks("checks", restore|off)
                         Enable/disable runtime checks set by /RTC. Checks: s (stack), u (uninitialized), c (type conversion).

#pragma check_stack(on|off)
                         Enable/disable stack probes for the functions that follow.
#pragma strict_gs_check(push) / (pop) / (on|off)
                         Force stack buffer security checks (/GS) even on functions the compiler wouldn't normally protect.

Floating Point

Pragma                   Description

#pragma fenv_access(on|off)
                         Tell the compiler whether the code accesses the FP environment
 (rounding mode, status flags). Disables FP optimizations that would break that.

#pragma float_control(precise, on|off)
                         Enable/disable precise FP model.

#pragma float_control(except, on|off)
                         Enable/disable FP exception semantics.

#pragma float_control(push) / (pop)
                         Save/restore float_control state.

#pragma fp_contract(on|off)
                         Allow/disallow FP contractions (e.g. fused multiply-add).

Include / Header

Pragma                   Description

#pragma once             Include this file only once per translation unit.

#pragma hdrstop          Mark the end of the precompiled header region. Everything before this line goes into the PCH.

#pragma include_alias("orig", "alias")
                         Map one include filename to another.

#pragma system_header    Treat the rest of this file as a system header (suppress warnings inside it). Useful when writing your own headers you want to treat as external.

Managed / CLR (C++/CLI)

Pragma                   Description

#pragma managed          Compile subsequent functions as managed (CLR) code.

#pragma unmanaged        Compile subsequent functions as native code, even inside a /clr TU.

#pragma make_public(type)
                         Give a native type public assembly visibility in a /clr build.

C++ / OOP

Pragma                   Description

#pragma vtordisp(on|off|n)
                         Control vtordisp hidden member generation for virtual base classes. Supports push/pop.

#pragma pointers_to_members(type [, inherit])
                         Control how pointers-to-members are represented. Types: full_generality, best_case, single_inheritance, multiple_inheritance, virtual_inheritance.

Loop / Parallelism

Pragma                   Description

#pragma loop(hint_parallel(n))
                         Hint that a loop should be parallelized across n threads.

#pragma loop(no_vector)
                         Prevent auto-vectorization of the next loop.

#pragma loop(ivdep)      Assert no loop-carried data dependencies (enables vectorization).

#pragma omp ...          OpenMP directives (parallel, for, sections, critical, barrier, etc.). Requires /openmp.

Miscellaneous

Pragma                   Description

#pragma init_seg(compiler|lib|user|"seg")
                         Control the order of global/static object initialization. compiler = earliest, user = latest.

#pragma setlocale("locale")
                         Set locale used during compilation for wide-char/string literals.

#pragma component(browser, on|off)
                         Enable/disable generation of browse info.

#pragma component(minrebuild, on|off)
                         Enable/disable minimal rebuild info tracking.

#pragma conform(name, show|on|off|push|pop)
                         Control conformance options (e.g. forScope). Mostly superseded by /Zc:.

#pragma push_macro("name")
                         Save the current definition of a macro onto a stack.

#pragma pop_macro("name")
                         Restore a previously pushed macro definition.

#pragma region "name"    Mark a collapsible region in the editor (Visual Studio only, no semantic effect).

#pragma endregion ["comment"]
                         End a #pragma region block.

A few notes worth keeping in mind:

Many pragmas that affect data/code placement (bss_seg, data_seg, code_seg, const_seg, pack) support a push/pop stack so you can save and restore state around a block of code — very useful in header files.
#pragma comment(lib, ...) is extremely common in Windows code as an alternative to passing .lib files on the linker command line.
#pragma warning(push/pop) + disable is the idiomatic way to suppress warnings in a targeted region without affecting the rest of the TU.
#pragma once is not technically standard C/C++ but is supported by essentially every modern compiler and is preferred over include guards in new code.